            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rohan Patel\u2019s San Francisco is mapped by a 2.8-mile bicycle commute, from his rent-controlled apartment in the Mission to the non-profit arts space in SoMa he helps run. At 54, he is a fixture in a city that constantly reinvents itself, a quiet guardian of its more fragile, creative soul.\n\nBorn in Fremont to Gujarati immigrants, Rohan was supposed to be an engineer. His parents sacrificed for a life of American stability, and a Bachelor's in Fine Arts from SF State was not part of their plan. The decision to pursue art was his first and most definitive act of rebellion, a choice that created a loving but persistent strain with his family. He moved across the bay in the early '90s, drawn to the city's bohemian grit before the first tech boom washed over it.\n\nHis early years were a blur of shared flats, waiting tables, and creating art that rarely sold. The turning point came not from a gallery sale, but from a volunteer gig installing an exhibition. He discovered a talent for logistics and an eye for curation, realizing he preferred orchestrating the show to being in it. He climbed the ladder patiently: art handler, gallery assistant, and finally, Exhibitions Manager. His work provides a steady $95,000 income, a figure that allows for a comfortable life only because of the apartment he\u2019s held for 25 years.\n\nA brief marriage to a fellow artist in his late thirties ended amicably, a casualty of two creative temperaments and the financial pressures of the city. Now, his social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of gallery owners, veteran artists, and chefs\u2014fellow \"lifers\" who remember the Mission before gourmet ice cream shops. His daily routine is a ritual: coffee from the same corner cafe, the rhythmic bike ride, the controlled chaos of an exhibition install, and an evening spent reading or attending a friend\u2019s gallery opening.\n\nRohan no longer dreams of fame or fortune. Instead, he aspires to curate one last, landmark exhibition\u2014a retrospective for an overlooked Bay Area artist, a final statement on the enduring power of art in a city obsessed with code. He is a man at peace with his choices, finding his meaning in the quiet, essential work of keeping the lights on for the city's imagination."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the drive home from SF State with his parents, the lights of the Bay Bridge glittering indifferently. He had just told them he was switching his major to Fine Arts. There was no yelling. Worse, there was a heavy, wounded silence from his father, whose hands gripped the steering wheel of the Camry. His mother just looked out the window. In that quiet car, suffocating with their disappointment, Rohan felt the first, terrifying and exhilarating pang of a life that would be entirely his own. It was the moment he chose himself.\n(Around age 20)\n\n2.\nIt was 1994, maybe 2 a.m. in a drafty, illegal gallery space South of Market. He was volunteering, dizzy from turpentine fumes and lack of sleep. After hammering the last nail, he stepped back to see the paintings perfectly spaced, lit by cheap clamp lights he\u2019d angled just so. In that moment, the composition of the *room* felt more dynamic and satisfying than any canvas he\u2019d ever tried to paint himself. It was a quiet revelation: he wasn't the artist. He was the one who made the art seen.\n(Mid-20s)\n\n3.\nThe day he signed the lease for his Mission apartment, he handed over a bundle of cash\u2014mostly crumpled twenties and tens from his waiting-tables job\u2014to the elderly landlady. She\u2019d liked that he was quiet. Standing alone for the first time in the empty living room, watching the late afternoon sun slant through the bay window and illuminate a universe of dust motes, he felt a profound sense of anchorage. This light, this floor, this was the foundation upon which the rest of his life could be built.\n(Late 20s)\n\n4.\nHe recalls a specific Saturday with his ex-wife, Elena. They were in their shared studio. She was wrestling with a huge, chaotic canvas, while he was meticulously organizing her brushes by size. He offered a practical suggestion about her composition, and she turned to him with a look that wasn't angry, but deeply sad. In her eyes, he saw the fundamental chasm between them: she was a storm, and he was a harbor. Their love was real, but their temperaments were simply immiscible, like oil and water.\n(Late 30s)\n\n5.\nRohan was on his bike, stopped at the lights on Folsom, watching a sleek, anonymous tech bus sigh to a halt. He glanced over at a mural on a brick wall\u2014a vibrant piece by an old friend that was now faded, slightly tagged. He felt not anger, but a surge of protective purpose. The bus represented the city\u2019s transient, lucrative present, but the mural was its memory. His job, he realized, wasn't just hanging art; it was tending to the city\u2019s stubborn, beautiful, and irreplaceable soul.\n(Within the last few years)"
